<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
I examined two Berlese slides, each bearing one female of 
<taxonomicName authority="Berlese, 1916" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1916" class="Arachnida" family="Ameroseiidae" genus="Epicriopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Epicriopsis" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Epicriopsis</taxonomicName>
collected from moss in Palermo, Sicily, and labelled 
<taxonomicName authority="G.Canestrini &amp; Fanzago, 1877" authorityName="G.Canestrini &amp; Fanzago" authorityYear="1877" class="Arachnida" family="Epicriidae" genus="Epicrius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Epicrius mollis" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mollis">Epicrius mollis</taxonomicName>
. As stated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Castagnoli, M" journalOrPublisher="Istituto Sperimentale per la Zoologia Agraria, Firenze, Italy" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" title="Catalogue of the Berlese Acaroteca." year="1985">Castagnoli and Pegazzano (1985)</bibRefCitation>
, they could most likely represent unlabelled and undesignated type specimens of 
<taxonomicName authority="Berlese, 1916" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1916" class="Arachnida" family="Ameroseiidae" genus="Epicriopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" infraspecific-rank="var." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Epicriopsis horrida var. sicula" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="horrida" variety="sicula">Epicriopsis horrida var. sicula</taxonomicName>
. Unfortunately, both female specimens are absolutely unsuitable for study due to the darkening of the mounting medium.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
